KMS and Secrets Manager are AWS's core security services for encryption and secrets management. KMS — Key Management Service — creates and controls the cryptographic keys used to encrypt data across AWS. Secrets Manager stores, rotates, and retrieves sensitive credentials so applications never hard-code passwords or API keys. Understanding both services is essential for the Solutions Architect exam and for designing secure architectures on AWS.

Let's start with KMS.

KMS is a managed service for creating and controlling cryptographic keys. It integrates with virtually every AWS service that stores or transmits data — S3, EBS, RDS, DynamoDB, Secrets Manager, SNS, SQS, Lambda, and more. The fundamental security property of KMS is that keys never leave KMS unencrypted. All cryptographic operations — encryption, decryption, signing — happen inside KMS's FIPS 140-2 validated hardware security modules. Your application never handles a raw key material directly. Every KMS API call is logged to CloudTrail, giving you a complete audit trail of who used which key, when, and from where.

There are three types of KMS keys distinguished by who owns and controls them. AWS managed keys are created automatically by AWS when you enable encryption on a service. For example, enabling server-side encryption on S3 creates a key named aws/s3. These keys are free, rotate automatically every year, and you cannot see or modify their key policy. Customer managed keys are created by you and give you full control — you define the key policy, set up rotation, share the key across accounts, and can disable or delete the key. Customer managed keys cost one dollar per month plus API call charges. AWS owned keys are shared across multiple AWS accounts and are entirely managed by AWS — you have no visibility into them.

Now let's look at symmetric versus asymmetric keys.

Symmetric keys use a single AES-256 key for both encryption and decryption. All AWS service integrations — S3, EBS, RDS, Secrets Manager — use symmetric keys. When you encrypt data using a KMS symmetric key, you must call KMS to decrypt it — the key never leaves KMS. Asymmetric keys are key pairs: a public key you can share and download, and a private key that never leaves KMS. Asymmetric keys are used for digital signatures and scenarios where an external party needs to encrypt data using your public key. For the exam, any question about encrypting data at rest in AWS services points to symmetric keys. Asymmetric keys appear only for digital signatures, JWT verification, or external-party encryption.

Now let's cover envelope encryption — one of the most important KMS concepts.

KMS has a four kilobyte limit on what it can encrypt directly. For large data, AWS uses envelope encryption. The process works like this. You call GenerateDataKey, passing your KMS key ID. KMS returns two things: a plaintext data encryption key and an encrypted version of that same data encryption key. You use the plaintext data encryption key to encrypt your data locally — this is fast because it happens in your application's memory, not inside KMS. You then store the encrypted data alongside the encrypted data encryption key, and immediately discard the plaintext data encryption key from memory.

To decrypt, you send the encrypted data encryption key to KMS. KMS uses your KMS key to decrypt it and returns the plaintext data encryption key. You use that to decrypt your data locally. The key insight is that your actual data never goes to KMS — only the small data encryption key does. The encrypted data encryption key is safe to store alongside your data because it is useless without access to the KMS key. All AWS service integrations use envelope encryption under the hood.

Now let's cover key policies and access control.

Key policies are the primary access control mechanism for KMS keys, and this is an important exam point: IAM policies alone are not sufficient to grant access to a KMS key. The key policy must explicitly allow the IAM principal. Every customer managed key has a key policy that must contain a statement enabling IAM — without it, no IAM policies for that key take effect.

KMS grants are an alternative way to delegate key permissions without modifying the key policy. You create a grant programmatically, specifying the principal and the allowed operations. AWS services use grants internally — for example, EBS creates a grant so it can use your key to encrypt a specific volume. Grants can be created and retired programmatically, which makes them useful for temporary or automated access scenarios.

For cross-account access, two things must both be true: the key policy in the owning account must allow the principal from the other account, and the IAM policy in the other account must allow the KMS actions on that key ARN.

Now let's cover key rotation and deletion.

Enabling automatic rotation on a customer managed key tells KMS to rotate the backing key material every year. The key ID, ARN, and any aliases remain the same — your application code does not change. KMS keeps all previous versions of the key material, so data encrypted with any previous version can still be decrypted. You can also rotate on-demand without waiting for the annual schedule.

Deleting a KMS key is irreversible and dangerous. Any data encrypted with the key becomes permanently unrecoverable once the key is deleted. For this reason, KMS enforces a mandatory waiting period of seven to thirty days before deletion takes effect. During this window you can cancel the deletion. If you want to prevent a key from being used without the risk of permanent data loss, disable the key instead of scheduling deletion.

Multi-region keys solve the problem of encrypting data in one region and decrypting it in another. A multi-region primary key and its replicas share the same key material and the same key ID prefix — starting with mrk. You can encrypt a value in us-east-1 and decrypt it in eu-west-1 without re-encrypting. This is important for DynamoDB Global Tables, globally replicated encrypted data, and disaster recovery scenarios.

Now let's look at how KMS integrates with specific services.

For S3, there are four encryption options. SSE-S3 lets AWS manage keys entirely with no KMS involvement — this is the default. SSE-KMS uses your KMS key, giving you CloudTrail visibility into every decryption and key policy control. SSE-C means you provide the encryption key on each request — AWS encrypts and decrypts but never stores your key. Client-side encryption means you encrypt the data before uploading — AWS never sees the plaintext.

An important SSE-KMS caveat: every S3 GET request triggers a KMS Decrypt API call. For high-throughput buckets this can exhaust KMS API rate limits. The solution is S3 Bucket Keys. With Bucket Keys enabled, S3 generates a short-lived data key from KMS and uses it for many objects in the bucket, reducing KMS API calls by up to ninety-nine percent.

For EBS, encryption is enabled at volume creation and uses either a customer managed key or the default aws/ebs key. Snapshots of encrypted volumes are automatically encrypted with the same key. Copying a snapshot to another region requires re-encrypting with a key in the destination region. You can also set a default encryption policy at the account level so all new EBS volumes are encrypted automatically.

For RDS, encryption must be enabled at instance creation — you cannot add encryption to an existing unencrypted instance. To encrypt an existing unencrypted RDS database, the process is: take a snapshot, copy the snapshot with encryption enabled, then restore a new instance from the encrypted snapshot.

Now let's cover Secrets Manager.

Secrets Manager stores sensitive credentials — database passwords, API keys, OAuth tokens — and retrieves them at runtime. Applications call GetSecretValue to retrieve the secret JSON instead of reading a hard-coded password from a config file. Secrets are encrypted at rest using a KMS key.

The defining feature of Secrets Manager over other storage options is automatic rotation. You configure a rotation schedule and a Lambda function. On each rotation, Lambda creates a new credential in the target service, updates the secret value in Secrets Manager, tests the new credential, and retires the old one. AWS provides built-in rotation Lambda templates for RDS, Aurora, Redshift, and DocumentDB. For any other secret type, you write a custom rotation Lambda.

Secrets Manager maintains multiple versions of each secret with staging labels. AWSCURRENT is the active version that applications retrieve by default. AWSPENDING is the new version being tested during rotation. AWSPREVIOUS is the last version before the current one. This versioning ensures there is always a valid credential available — rotation causes zero downtime.

Secrets can also be replicated to multiple regions. The replica stays in sync with the primary secret and is useful for multi-region applications and disaster recovery.

Now let's compare Secrets Manager with SSM Parameter Store.

SSM Parameter Store is a simpler, cheaper service that stores configuration values and secrets. Standard parameters are free, and Advanced parameters cost five cents per parameter per month. Parameter Store does not have built-in automatic rotation — you must write your own rotation logic. Encrypted parameters use KMS SecureString type. The maximum parameter size is four kilobytes for Standard and eight kilobytes for Advanced.

The exam decision is straightforward. If the scenario requires automatic secret rotation — especially for database credentials — use Secrets Manager. If you need to store application configuration, feature flags, or non-rotating secrets at minimal cost, use SSM Parameter Store.

